  "content": [
    {
      "id": { "value": "topic-color-wheel" },
      "title": "The Color Wheel",
      "type": "topic",
      "orderIndex": 0,
      "description": "Understanding the color wheel and how primary, secondary, and tertiary colors relate to each other.",
      "learningObjectives": [
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-1" },
          "statement": "Identify the three primary colors and explain why they are called primary",
          "bloomsLevel": "understand"
        },
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-2" },
          "statement": "Create secondary colors by mixing primary colors",
          "bloomsLevel": "apply"
        }
      ],
      "transcript": {
        "segments": [
          {
            "id": "seg-1",
            "type": "introduction",
            "content": "Welcome to our exploration of color theory! Today we're going to learn about one of the most important tools in any artist's toolkit: the color wheel.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "enthusiastic"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-2",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "The color wheel is a circular diagram that shows the relationships between colors. It was first developed by Sir Isaac Newton in 1666 when he discovered that white light, when passed through a prism, separates into a spectrum of colors.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "slow",
              "emotionalTone": "informative"
            },
            "checkpoint": {
              "type": "comprehension",
              "question": "Who first developed the concept of the color wheel?"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-3",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "At the heart of the color wheel are the three primary colors: red, yellow, and blue. These are called primary colors because they cannot be created by mixing other colors together. They are the foundation from which all other colors are made.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "explanatory",
              "emphasis": ["primary colors", "red", "yellow", "blue"]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-4",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "When you mix two primary colors together, you get secondary colors. Red and yellow make orange. Yellow and blue make green. Blue and red make purple, which is also called violet. These three secondary colors sit between the primary colors on the wheel.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "slow",
              "emotionalTone": "instructional"
            },
            "checkpoint": {
              "type": "comprehension",
              "question": "What secondary color do you get when you mix red and yellow?"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-5",
            "type": "summary",
            "content": "So remember: the color wheel starts with three primary colors that cannot be mixed from other colors, and these combine to create three secondary colors. This gives us six fundamental colors that form the basis of all color relationships.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "concluding",
              "pauseAfter": "PT3S"
            }
          }
        ],
        "totalDuration": "PT8M"
      },
