    {
      "id": { "value": "topic-color-harmony" },
      "title": "Color Harmony",
      "type": "topic",
      "orderIndex": 1,
      "description": "Learn how colors work together to create visually pleasing combinations using complementary, analogous, and triadic color schemes.",
      "learningObjectives": [
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-3" },
          "statement": "Identify complementary colors on the color wheel",
          "bloomsLevel": "understand"
        },
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-4" },
          "statement": "Apply color harmony principles to create a pleasing color palette",
          "bloomsLevel": "apply"
        }
      ],
      "transcript": {
        "segments": [
          {
            "id": "seg-h1",
            "type": "introduction",
            "content": "Now that you understand the color wheel, let's explore how colors work together. This is called color harmony, and it's the secret to creating artwork and designs that feel balanced and beautiful.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "engaging"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-h2",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "Complementary colors are colors that sit directly opposite each other on the color wheel. Red and green are complementary. Blue and orange are complementary. Yellow and purple are complementary. When placed next to each other, complementary colors create strong contrast and make each other appear more vibrant.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "slow",
              "emotionalTone": "informative",
              "emphasis": ["opposite", "complementary", "vibrant"]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-h3",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "Analogous colors are colors that sit next to each other on the color wheel, like blue, blue-green, and green. These colors naturally look good together because they share similar qualities. Analogous color schemes feel calm and harmonious.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "calm"
            },
            "checkpoint": {
              "type": "comprehension",
              "question": "What type of color scheme uses colors that are next to each other on the wheel?"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-h4",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "A triadic color scheme uses three colors that are evenly spaced around the color wheel, forming a triangle. The primary colors, red, yellow, and blue, form one triadic scheme. Another example is orange, green, and purple. Triadic schemes are vibrant and balanced.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "explanatory"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-h5",
            "type": "summary",
            "content": "Understanding color harmony helps you make intentional choices in your artwork. Complementary colors create excitement, analogous colors create calm, and triadic colors create balance with variety. Experiment with these schemes to see what effects you can create!",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "encouraging",
              "pauseAfter": "PT2S"
            }
          }
        ],
        "totalDuration": "PT7M"
      },
