    {
      "id": { "value": "topic-warm-cool" },
      "title": "Warm and Cool Colors",
      "type": "topic",
      "orderIndex": 2,
      "description": "Discover how colors can convey temperature and mood through the concepts of warm and cool colors.",
      "learningObjectives": [
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-5" },
          "statement": "Categorize colors as warm or cool based on their position on the color wheel",
          "bloomsLevel": "understand"
        },
        {
          "id": { "value": "lo-6" },
          "statement": "Explain how warm and cool colors affect the mood of artwork",
          "bloomsLevel": "analyze"
        }
      ],
      "transcript": {
        "segments": [
          {
            "id": "seg-wc1",
            "type": "introduction",
            "content": "Colors can make us feel things. Some colors feel energetic and exciting, while others feel calm and peaceful. This is because colors have what we call temperature, and we divide them into warm colors and cool colors.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "intriguing"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-wc2",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "Warm colors include red, orange, and yellow, along with variations like red-orange and yellow-orange. These colors remind us of fire, sunshine, and warmth. They tend to feel energetic, exciting, and can seem to advance toward the viewer.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "warm",
              "emphasis": ["fire", "sunshine", "energetic"]
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-wc3",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "Cool colors include blue, green, and purple, along with their variations. These colors remind us of water, sky, and nature. They tend to feel calm, peaceful, and can seem to recede into the background.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "calm",
              "emphasis": ["water", "sky", "peaceful"]
            },
            "checkpoint": {
              "type": "comprehension",
              "question": "Would you describe purple as a warm or cool color?"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-wc4",
            "type": "explanation",
            "content": "Artists use warm and cool colors intentionally to create mood. A painting dominated by warm oranges and reds might feel passionate or intense. A painting with mostly blues and greens might feel serene or melancholy. The balance between warm and cool colors helps tell a story.",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "slow",
              "emotionalTone": "thoughtful"
            }
          },
          {
            "id": "seg-wc5",
            "type": "summary",
            "content": "Remember, warm colors are on one half of the color wheel and cool colors are on the other. By choosing warm or cool colors, you can control how your artwork makes people feel. This is one of the most powerful tools in an artist's palette!",
            "speakingNotes": {
              "pace": "moderate",
              "emotionalTone": "empowering",
              "pauseAfter": "PT3S"
            }
          }
        ],
        "totalDuration": "PT6M"
      },
